This is a salt and pepper cellar in form of a wobbler toy.

You need two halves for a wobbler!
Preferably in black and white since to the number of holes is equal (and hidden) and can't indicate whether it contains salt or pepper.

Magnets per wobbler: 8 x [4mm diameter, 2mm height, polarization direction: polar]

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Notes:

Higher infill is better.
Rough resolution is ok.
Smooth convex outer surfaces => easy to post process.

glue in magnets & polish if desired.

For one wobbler You'll need to buy eight magnets (better more - they like to get lost) with a diameter of 4mm and thickness of 2mm. These magnets need to be magnetized axially that is north and south at bottom and top surface respectively.
The magnets need to be glued in with the right pattern of polarity or else the halves will not connect in the right way. The magnets at the sharp ends of both halves of the wobbler need one polarity sticking outwards. The magnets at the flat ends of both halves of the wobbler need the other polarity sticking outward. See pictures.
Be sure you have the right polarity when you glue the magnets in (you may mark them). This can't be undone!
Cyanoacrylate (superglue) works fine for gluing. Use toothpicks. Avoid getting glue on the hull.

The wobbler in the photographs are printed with PLA plastic and polished more smooth with the solvent methyl-ethyl-ketone (MEK) aka Butanone
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butanone
(mechanical rubbing with a piece of cotton needed)

title: Microswitch holder for filament detection (two versions)

description.text:
A holder for detecting filament using a microswitch. Used for pausing prints when filament runs out.
If you want to put it next to the filament roll (easier, no need to route wiring through signal chain, but a lot of filament remains unprinted), print "Shell 1" and "Shell 2", any normal material for 3D-printing should work.
If you are going to put it directly on the extruder (If you have a direct extruder, you have to route the wiring through the signal chain, but only a few cm of filament will stay unprinted. It might be better to print it with ABS in this case, PLA might get soft in this hotter area.), print "Shell1 (for head with teflon).stl" and "Shell 2". When installing, cut off 1,5 cm of teflon tube and insert it in the bottom hole of the shell1 and the top hole of the extruder where you would insert the teflon usually.
Connect the microswitch to OctopPi header as shown on the hand-drawn diagram (3,3V through the microswitch to parallel-connected pull-down resistor and capacitor, microswitch side connected to GPIO2, other side to ground), use the Octopi header pinout (downloaded from Raspberry Pi website for your reference) as reference for pin numbers. You could also just connect the microswitch between the IO pin and ground, but you might have problems with noise (false alarms).
Install Filament sensor plugin in OctoPi and configure as instructed: If you use the same pinout as me, add the following lines to YAML (easiest way is to use YAMLPatcher plugin):

plugins:
  filament:
    pin: 2
    bounce: 400

Restart and you are done :)
Each time the filament runs out, the Octopi will enter pause mode.

Printer:

Craftbot original

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

25 %

Notes:

Rotate both parts with smooth side down for printing. ABS or PLA work equally well, unless you are going to put it on the printing head, in this case ABS might be better.
Shell 1 and 2 do not need supports, Shell1 (for head with teflon) probably not as well, but you might use it to get a nicer looking hole for the teflon.

Installation and use

Insert a normal 3D-printer microswitch (the type with the little wheel at the end of the arm) onto the little pegs and screw together using 3 M3 screws and nuts.
Version near the filament roll (Shell 1):
Attach to printer. Insert the filament through the bottom hole, insert the Teflon tube in the hole on top.
Version on the printing head (Shell1 (for head with teflon).stl):
Jam a 1,5 cm long piece of teflon tube into the extruder where teflon tube would normally go, put the bottom hole of the Shell1 on top of that. Insert the filament from top, insert the Teflon tube in the hole on top.

comments.text:
What's the direction of the capacitor? I'm a newbie in electronics and I see capacitors have polarity..
Also, are both capacitor and resistor connected to GND (pin 6)?
comments.author: papinist

comments.text:
Most capacitors do not have polarity, but some (electrolytic) do. The 100 nF cap of the type you are most likely to buy or find in a drawer is not polarised, so any orientation would work. Is a cap is polarised, it usually has markings indicating either the negative or the positive side. In that case, connect negative side to ground.
Yes, the inverted T is a symbol for ground (GND), both the capacitor and resistor are connected to it..

description.text:
I've got my home territory gate access keychain. It was designed to be compact, so it used A27 (MN27) type 12V battery with low capacity. This is quite expensive battery, also sometimes it is hard to find such rare battery in my location. I found the replacement - A23 (MN21) type 12V battery with much higher capacity, lower priced and wider distributed. It has the same length, but 10mm diameter instead of 7mm for A27.
I did model of the new keychain than holds new battery type and the electronics board. Red trasparent window shall be also taken from the old keychain. Finally the keychain works fine with it.
Keychain_top and keychain_bottom files are ready for print, but keychain_top requires support to print main surface. IMHO no problem to print keychain_top 'as is' with PLA and fan. But I used ABS plastic w/o fan, so the support tends to mix with the lower print surface and actually deeply melts it with support. This is why I also added support surface to keychain_top_surf_support. It still requires the support, but the support melts with this additional surface. After the print end the support surface can be cleaned with blunt knife that opens some textured top surface instead of melted one. Use keychain_top_surf_support when print with ABS!
Any suggestions are welcome.

DO THIS ONLY AT YOUR ON RISK! IF THERE IS A LEAKAGE INSIDE YOUR PC IT CAN FRY YOUR COMPONENTS! I DON'T TAKE ANY RESPONSIBILITY TO ANY DAMAGE OR HARM THIS DESIGNS MAY CAUSE TO YOU!

Now with this out of the way lets start:
This design is one of the reasons I bought myself a 3d printer 2 years ago. The goal is to make custom parts for my water cooling system of my PC.
The hardest part is to actually get parts watertight. ABS printing is a must as far as I know. unless you seal your part completely with silicone or an other coating.

I printed this part with the 13/10 nipple looking towards the heated bed and I used support material only from the build platform (not inside the round cylinder)
The ABS was then acetone treated. I used several Q-Tips that were soaked with acetone to disperse the solved ABS on the surface.
After the acetone was evaporated I placed a thin layer of silicone on each nipple and on critical parts and let it cure. The fixation rings are important to have enough pressure of the tube to the nipples. Maybe you need to re-design this rings as the got a bit tight.
The parts were then tested outside the PC first using a small pump and reservoir. After checking that no leakage was observable in my test setup outside the PC I installed it inside the PC and had it under surveillance for some more time. It's working like a charm ever since.

The arms of the default microswitches of the 3KU delta printer have a annoying habbit of bending. When this happens the printer needs to be calibrated again, also with each bend of the arms the arm gets a little weaker and the accuracy deteriorates.

This endstop brackets are designed to replace the default brackets and allow the microswitches to be used without the arms. With this the accuracy is higher and the system is a little tougher. Also becouse the microswitches are now on the outside part of the printer the chance that the bowden tube or any other cable hits the microswitch is a lot smaller.

Extra parts needed:

  • 3x M3 screw 16mm
  • 3x M3 nut
  • Endstop cables (the default cables are a little to short)
  • 3x microswitch (if you want to keep the original microswitches)

Tools needed:

  • Drill + 3.2mm drill bit

3KU delta

Mounting
  • Slide the bracket over the printer plate and drill a 3.2mm hole trough the top hole trough the printer plate, make sure you drill straight.
  • Mount the (new) microswitch onto the top of the plate, make sure the switching part points to the outside.
  • Put a M3 nut into the nuttrap
  • Slide the bracket over the printer plate and use a M3 screw to fasten the bracket onto the printer.
  • Connect the microswitch cable to the RAMPS board.
  • Make sure the timing belts don't rub against the switch and first test by hand that the switches work (you can use M119 to see which endstop triggers)

description.text:
Remix of toilet seat hinge http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:39750, with the added ability to create either a lid hinge or a seat hinge.

To customize, use OpenSCAD or the Customizer app. For a hinge which attaches to the seat, choose a sidedness of 0; for a hinge which attaches to the lid, choose a sidedness of 1. The sidedness variable affects whether the screw head cutouts are placed on the same side as the hinge or the opposite side of the hinge. So choose either 0 or 1 for sidedness and then confirm that the screw head cutouts are on the appropriate side of the hinge for your application.

See also the original thing for more instructions. Basically, you can choose the screw placement, the dimensions, the geometry of the hinge, etc., by keying those variables into the top of the SCAD file or using the Customizer app.

I've included STLs for a lid hinge and a seat hinge that worked for my lid and seat. But I assume that my measurements will not work for you. So I encourage you to specify your own measurements in the SCAD file or Customizer.

Notes:

I used an infill of 25%. One of my hinges cracked when I overtightened a screw, but it is still holding strong.

title: Hang your Spools from the Ceiling

description.text: As always, horizontal surfaces are limited, so I decided to hang the filament spools from the ceiling above my Thing-o-matic. I designed a pair of clips to hold the filament when it is not being used, and a separator to keep the spools from rubbing against each other. The spools are on plastic plumbing pipes, hanging from chains.

Hanging the spools on plastic pipe posed two main problems -- how to keep the spools apart and how to hang the pipes.   
Hanging the pipes with chains allows height adjustment and ability to hit the joists in the ceiling. I added wood strips which are screwed into the ceiling and then hooks for the chain. You can see how this works in the picture. The end-caps are from the plumbing aisle -- they are caps for the pipes. I slit the end with a saw and added a hose clamp to make sure they would not slide off. Then I put a screw into the ends to hold the chain.  
Now, about the spool separators. I designed them in OpenSCAD so you can vary them as you wish. I used pipe which is called 3/4 inch, but has about 1 inch outside diameter. Then I used an M3 x 16mm bolt for the tightening screw.  
Finally, I designed two filament clips for the filament that hangs down. As shown in the pictures, one is mounted on a workbench, and one is on the top of the TOM, The one on top of the TOM has support material in the slot that slips over the printer. It should be very thin, so you should be able to cut it out with a fine tooth hobby saw. Clean it up so it slides over the top. The clips have a snap-in action so that the filament stays tight. Sorry, this was not created in OpenSCAD, so I don't have that file.

title: The PrintBone: a fully printable playable trombone
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A 3d printable trombone. Fully parameterized in OpenSCAD, see https://github.com/pieterbos/PrintBone and check the wiki there for instructions on creating your own trombone design.

See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2252952 for an updated version that prints and looks better. Soundwise it's the same.

The bell correspond to a large bore 8.5 inch symphonic bell. Fits a Bach 42 or Bach 50 slide, or a yamaha slide - possibly more brands.

The slide is a PVC slide. It can be done with any kind of tubes by editing the .scad file you can find on github. Fits the printed bell or a bach 42b.

The OpenSCAD file also works to create very nice working carbon fiber outer slides for different trombones, if you can find the correct tube diameter. A bach 42B inner slide fits widely available 15mm diameter tubes, but 14.9mm would be better. See github for improved designs for that purpose, that print without any support.

See https://soundcloud.com/pieter-bos-2013025 for a recording of both a regular brass bell and this bell. Can you guess which one is which?
It also has a recording of the pla slide, work in progress with still a leak somewhere and it will sound better later.

Printing instructions for the bell

I printed it in PLA on an original Prusa I3 MK2 with 0.2mm layer height. Choose whatever infill you like. Print time somewhere between 25-30 hours, but you can probably do a lot faster with a 0.6 or 0.8mm nozzle and a faster printer.

The bell flare is cut for an at least 21x22x20 printer. If you have a smaller printer, you will have to adjust those two files.

Print the tuning slide with the pegs upward, and support enabled. The two small midair rafts will be supported and make for a much more stable part. They can be easily broken off later.

A two piece bell flare that can be more easily printed without support is available as a setting in the OpenSCAD file, it has not yet been tested.

Printing the slide parts

add lots of infill or even solid for the inner handslide brace because it needs to be stiff!
The rest, just print whatever is the most airtight.
I printed the leadpipe in spiral vase mode with a 0.3mm nozzle and 0.37mm wall thickness, 0.1mm layer height.
The leadpipe is relatively bright. If you don't like it, increase the venturi diameter in the openscad file a bit.

Bell assembly instructions
  1. Print tuning slide and both neckpipe parts
  2. Sand connections and test fit parts and parts to trombone
  3. If they fit, continue. If not, download openscad file and adjust clearance parameters. You can keep the tuning slide even if fit is not correct, it will not be altered
  4. Print the rest of the parts
  5. Sand all connections to make a good fit
  6. Test all parts for airtightness. Use superglue to fix any leaks (perhaps acetone for ABS?)
  7. Glue all connections except for bell flare
  8. Test assembled bell without flare for leaks and fix them. It's easier to close the ends without the flare attached.
  9. Glue bell flare

Tips:

  • You can use a practice mute to seal the bell when checking for leaks.
  • Use soapy water to find the location of leaks. WARNING: soapy water slowly dissolves superglue :)
Slide assembly instructions

Get 2 meters of 3/4 and 5/8 inch PVC pipe.

  1. Print parts
  2. Test for leaks. Fix all leaks. Coating with an epoxy lacquer might help.
  3. Cut the upper inner slide tube to correct length. Assemble without gluing.
  4. Assemble rest of smaller tube and cut to same length.
  5. assemble outer slide tube, check length and cut.
  6. test the slide. Glue the parts
  7. put stockings on a piece of tubing you have left after step 5 and sand the stockings with increasing grit sandpaper. I used 180 - 320 then 600. They should be very smooth.
  8. Put stockings on trombone, check fit and glue.
  9. Lubricate stockings with slide cream (slide-o-mix and yamaha lubricant do NOT work well)

If parts do not fit, check the openscad file and you can input your own measurements.

Stilt Assembly

after parts are printed, use hot glue to attach the correct lengths of EL wire in the slots on the springs. feed EL wire through hole in center of the foot piece and solder to controller. Pull EL wire tight through this hole as you use epoxy to cement each spring into it's hole.

insert a velcro strap into slots on the top of each foot. while wearing shoes, slide your feet in and you're off!

When I saw this challenge i knew i wanted to build a pair of stilts. Rather than a single pole, traditional stilt i decided to build a shorter, dual support stilt, as stilt walking takes a lot of work and i was looking for something I could wear longer at a party. I began with drywall stilts as the inspiration. Then i thought, I should totally make holes in them so you can see through them. that evolved into this design, which is meant to look a little like springs. They are a lot of fun to walk on, and EL wire is incorporated to make your haunted adventures glow in the dark!

title: Classic Erector set to LEGO (with lego tools) in OpenSCAD

description.text: My grandson is a great LEGO builder, but now I am giving him a classic Erector Set to expand his abilities. Along with it, I thought we could create a set of transition pieces that would allow mixing the two. I started with the library contained in http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13531/#files but modified it. Read the instructions to see how to make the parts shown -- a connector from the LEGO block to a classic square girder, a connection from the square girder to the LEGO blocks, and a flat plate to screw on the top of an Erector plate.

Three files are needed for the SCAD program, lego.scad, lego_dimens.scad, and ErectorToLego.scad. lego.scad contains the modules that are used in building LEGO blocks, lego_dimens.scad is the source of the basic LEGO dimensions and may need to be modified slightly for your printer. The main build of the parts is in ErectorToLego.scad.  
The main things you may want to change in building the pieces are the number of "knobs" in width and length and the thickness of the pieces. There are three primary modules in the file -- one to create the transition from LEGO to Erector (Top_Er), one for the transition from Erector to LEGO (Bottom_Er) and one to make flat plates with screw holes (Er_plate).  The first three parameters in each are the number of knobs wide, then long, then the thickness.   
An additional parameter in Top_Er specifies whether reinforcement will be added inside the bottom of the block.  
In Bottom_Er and Er_plate parameters allow an extension of the knobs (in mm) and creating a chamfer on the knobs. This may allow a better fit for these pieces.  
In Er_plate, the span_holes parameter sets how many holes are spanned (inclusive of the end holes) for the screw holes through the Erector plate.  
The modules provided should be useful for other transition peices, either to Erector sets or to other construction sets.

description.text: customized with 3D Slash!

English version:
The aim is to avoid filament unravelling / to protect filament against dust and other contamination.

The part is adaptable, therefore you could use it for all the spools on the market.

Before creating a part, you should measure the spool width from one disk to the other one (take into account that the thickness of each disk should be divided by two - Distance from neutral axis to neutral axis)

After, you could assemble different part widths (see exploded view).
Pay attention to use the correct distances (For exemple: 8.5mm/12mm at both extremities & 14mm/7mm at the center)

Once the assembled part is printed, you could remove all the plastic supports around the filament guide (Use a cutter and a wire cutter).
After, you could wind the filament around the spool. Pay attention that both disks are correctly centered by the part gutters.
It's possible to use one or two elastics (120mm*1.5mm recommended) but it depends on the torque (caused by the friction) your extruder is able to support without printing damages.

I advise you to use a piece of tape to link the belt. By pulling the filament you will see that the force is low with this solution (possible to use ropes...)

Pay attention that this holder could not replace completely a filament guide as lateral forces applied on it are limited. This solution is a complement to your actual guide.

Enjoy!

Version Française:
Le but de cette ceinture est d'empêcher que le filament ne puisse s'échapper de la bobine mais aussi éviter toute contamination extérieure du filament (poussière, ...)

Le modèle est évolutif, il peut donc logiquement s'adapter à la plupart des bobines existantes.
Pour créer son propre modèle, il suffit de mesurer la largeur extérieure de votre bobine et d'y soustraire 1x l'épaisseur d'un des deux disques. (Distance fibre neutre / fibre neutre)
Ensuite il suffit de créer l'empilage que vous désirez (voir vue éclatée plus haut).
Attention de bien respecter les hauteurs à additionner (par ex 8.5mm/12mm aux extrémités et 14mm/7mm au centre)!!!!!!

Une fois le modèle imprimé, il faut enlever les supports à la main au niveau du passage du filament (cutter et pince coupante conseillés).
Ensuite il suffit d'enrouler la ceinture autour de la bobine en s'assurant que les disques de la bobine soient prisonniers des gouttières du modèle.
Il est possible de mettre 1 ou deux élastique autour de la "ceinture" (modèle 120mm*1.5mm conseillé), tout dépend du couple dû à l'effort de friction que votre extrudeur peut encaisser sans altérer l'impression.

Je vous conseille plutôt de boucler la "ceinture" à l'aide d'un morceau de scotch, vous verrez en tirant sur le filament que l'effort et faible. (il est possible d'utiliser de la ficelle aussi)

Attention, la ceinture ne peut pas se substituer complètement à un guide fil étant donné que l'effort latéral que l'on peut appliquer sur le filament est faible. Cette ceinture est plutôt un complément à votre moyen de guidage.

Enjoy!

description.text:
As a subtle enhancement of my toilet roll holder I came up with this adaptation of the idea of changing the direction of the material like with this Woodini Stool made by Bakery Design.

Because nearly 30 mm of material are pretty hard to cut on a desktop cnc I went with gluing up three layers of 9,6 mm material. I nested the parts exactly with gaps of 3 mm to save some cutting.

The build was done on a desktop cnc-machine from Stepcraft from 9,6 mm birch plywood using a spiral-toothed 3 mm flute. The surface got some clear spray-paint to intensify the wood structure and to make it water-resistant.

The two parts are joined by adding a dowel and a corresponding hole. As it needs to come apart in order to change the roll, I used two magnets to lock them.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more interesting designs.

description.text:
This is only a derivative of it's parent in spirit. It's a completely new openscad file.
I liked the idea of the parent but I felt that it would be nice to have a little bit more keeping the bearing X Stage perpendicular to the Y Rods. So, this is a spacer for the linear bearings that matches up with 3 of the screws that hold the X stage together.

Print it out.
There are a couple of version of the file. One with a bearing hole of 16mm, 16.1mm and 16.2mm
If the 16mm is too tight you can print out a larger one (you may want to start with the 16.1mm one)
To get the file for the back side, scale by -1 in replicatorg. You may have to sand/file/cut the hole for the bearing a little bigger to get an easy fit (or adjust the openscad file)
You may also have to sand down the piece so it isn't quite as tall so that the snap rings can fit (or adjust the openscad file).
The height worked perfectly for me, the hole was a bit tight but I figured that was better than having a lot of slop in it. 2 SW06 bearings 4 snap rings of the appropriate size ( 5/8" I believe ). Remove the X Stage from the bot.
Push out the stock bushings.
Install 1 snap ring on each bearing and press them in from the inside of the stage.
Push the printed pieces on from the outside and secure with the snap ring (but turn them perpendicular so that it doesn't hit the screw heads. Remove the screws, being careful not to lose the nuts, rotate the piece and install slightly longer screws (20mm?) to attach it. I removed the bottom screw & nut and then held the top nut in and removed the screw and then removed the other screw while holding the piece level so the nut didn't fall out and then replaced the screws and the other nut. The openscad file generates the front piece only, I just flipped it by scaling it by -1 in replicatorg.

title: Monoprice MP Select Mini 3D Printer glass bed Clips

description.text:
I no longer own this printer so support for this is limited! There have been reports of the left side clips binding so you may need to make your own modifications depending on how tight the clips fit.

I wanted to add a glass bed to my Monoprice Mini Select 3D Printer but could find no clips for it so I created my own. These clips will allow you to level your bed and you can remove the glass easily for print removal. I found a 130mmx130mmx3mm glass bed on eBay that fits well for this print bed. I also worked with a 140mmx140mmx3mm glass bed but it sticks out in places. Note that these clips do not clip down on the glass, but push in tightly to hold glass in place.

You need to print two of the Back Left corner clips (goes on Back Left and Front Right corners) and two of the Back Right corner clips (goes on Back Right and Front Left corners).

Make sure you print out a Z-axis shim first and install before trying to use glass plate!

The clip is customizable if you have your own glass plate it should work for both larger and smaller glass plates if you customize it.

  1. Make sure you print out a Z azis shim first that matches your glass bed thickness.
  2. Make sure you measure to get the right height for the latch on the clips if you are not using a 3mm glass plate with 3mm z-axis shim.
  3. Estimate the glass plate to be smaller in length & width so that the clips push tightly against the glass.

I think this is the final version! Note: I printed with 100% infill and black ABS on this printer for the final version.

I recommend printing just one clip and seeing how it fits and making modifications in customizer or openscad before printing them all!

Resolution:

2.0

Infill:

100%

Notes:

I recommend printing in ABS since its on a heated bed... but since this bed doesn't get all that hot might be alright with PLA. Supports really only need inside the latch but can possibly get away with no support. I generally print parts like this with high infill. I used 100% infill to prevent the narrow tabs from breaking.

This clip is supposed to fit tightly or the glass will move. However, if some places are too tight you may need to sand a slight amount. I usually use an emery board for this. For me, one of the clips was too tight underneath against the screw mount so I had to sand the edge of the clip latch. You can tell this if the clip doesn't slide up nicely into place when you release tension on the spring.

description.text:
I tried for awhile to find a good quality set of open-ear bluetooth headphones. I was unsuccessful. Since I couldn't buy it, I decided to make it!!

With a set of Grado SR80's, the PCB from a cheap set of Bluetooth headphones, and a headphone pad thing, you can make a great-sounding set of 'phones that work either wired or wirelessly.

Grados: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00L1LXOWS/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
Cheap-o BT Headphones:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00M9DBBK4/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
Headphone Headband Pad:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00OF722LY/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

The design is three parts:

  1. the "can" that holds the drivers from the SR80's (print two of these)
  2. the "board" case that holds the PCB + microphone from the cheap BT headphones.
  3. the batt case that holds the LiPo battery from the cheap BT headphones.

I'm not affiliated w/ grado, amazon, or the folks that make the cheap BT headphones in any way. I'm just a guy who was obsessed with getting a set of open-ear BT headphones!!

Printer:

Zortrax m200

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

40%

Notes:

I printed ABS, PLA would probably work fine.

Assembly

You'll be cutting wires on a LiPo battery. This can get really dangerous if you don't know what you're doing. Please don't burn your house down.

  1. Remove foam pads from your grados.
  2. Carefully detach the grado "cans" from the yoke on the headband. Be careful, you need the yoke!
  3. Using a hairdryer, warm up each can, then twist the driver away from the backing can.
  4. Note the polarity of the wires on the back of the driver. (May need a multimeter for this.)
  5. Desolder the original wire from each driver. Hang on to the wire and the backing can in case you want to reverse this mod later!)
  6. Tear the drivers and earpads off of the cheap BT headphones. It's fine to cut the wires heading to the drivers but DO NOT cut the battery wire yet.
  7. At the battery, cut ONE of the wires, leaving enough wire to re-solder an extension. Tape the wire so it doesn't short.
  8. Cut and tape the other battery wire.
  9. Unscrew & remove the PCB from the cheap BT headphones.
  10. Desolder the wires on the PCB that used to lead to the drivers and the battery.
  11. Using some >= 20awg wire (i used an old telephone cable,) solder wire from PCB to L driver. Make sure you pass the wire through the "can"!
  12. Solder to PCB for batt and R driver. Pass cable through large hole in board housing, leave enough wire to go across headband, then back through hole in batt housing. Solder wire to R driver (make sure pass through can!.)
  13. Slide button into slot, screw PCB into board housing.
  14. solder wire to battery.
  15. Pop the microphone into the slot inside the board housing, dab a bit of silicone or hot glue on it to keep it in place.
  16. Zip-tie battery in place to batt housing.
  17. Zip-tie around cables just inside and just outside of each housing (to prevent them from yanking off solder joints.)
  18. Slide the drivers into the cans - they should bottom out on the "ribs".
  19. Screw or zip-tie the cans to the housings.
  20. Clip the cans into your yoke from the grados.
  21. Secure you wire to top of headband w/ the cloth headband thing.
  22. Post a pic of your awesome new headphones to the comments!

Enjoy them!!

RepRap

Printer:

BCN3D+

No

No

0.1 or 0.2

80%

Notes:

Important!

Print the parts with the "face" facing the print bed. You will get the best results!

3D Printing and Post-printing

Both items are easy to print. They need no supports and the two printed parts are easy to assemble without glue. You only need to make two small holes in the "eyes" of the item using a thin pin previously heated with a lighter. Pay attention to the zone where the hole must be done! It must fit the channel in the back side...

After making the holes, you must assemble the clip in the slot and make sure it keeps tightly in place.

Adding the squirting system

Well, we have the component ready but the job isn't finished yet!

We need to assemble the squirting system. For this step you need two cheap and easy to find parts:

  • A plastic syringe (I used a 20 ml one I had at home but bigger or smaller ones will work as well)
  • A piece of flexible plastic pipe. In this case we need a Ø 6 mm outer pipe as the backside conexion is designed to fit this pipe size. This is a very common item you can find in gardening stores for example.

First of all we must check the length of pipe we need in order to hide the pipe and the syringe behind our clothing. Fit the pipe in the housing the printed part has and the other end in the water-filled syringe. The pipe will go through our chest to our arm and it will finish in our hand where the syringe will do the rest...

Please note that some glue (like superglue) will be a good idea if you want to get a tight assembly and don't want to get yourself wet (see the videos to get the idea ;))

A piece of advice...

If you realize your friends are getting angry (and too wet!) it is time to stop and move to another place ;)

title: Parabellum Rocket -- spins in flight, looks like a TOW missile

description.text:
I originally built this the traditional way, but it took so much abuse it eventually fell apart.  Now, V2 is all plastic.  Print this in 0.3mm resolution at 50% infill and you have a mean looking rocket.  This has its fins slightly canted to have an initial angle of attack.  Once the rocket has accelerated past the launch rail it should start to spin.  V1 flew beautifully, V2 should also.  If you want one printed, I can be convinced to make kits of these for a small fee.  
Update 11/25/2013: I added a few enhancements...First, when I assembled my rocket and weighed it, it was at 6.7oz, which is well beyond the max takeoff weight for a C6-5 engine (4oz max).  So clearly I needed a D engine, but rather than mess with the design, I added an extension to mount a D motor, which has a max lift capacity of 14oz.  This approach lets me keep the CG forward and the rocket looks even more like a TOW.  And, the engine mount has a slot for the engine hook.  With the mount you should not go past 10oz which keeps you inside the flight envelope, but be warned, it's gonna go....Also, don't bother with a C11-3, as that still has you at the bottom end.  Finally, I added some rails to give the joined tubes some external support.  I used a particularly potent type of CA glue and used some ground plastic as filler.  Once filed, the gaps are gone and it's going to look fabulous when painted.  Shame if it vanishes in the sky.

Assemble the parts, and consider a raft or some 'mouse ears) about 2mm high to support the fins.  I used a concentric ring as a raft under the fin-can (applies to FDM printers more than sintering or STL printers.

description.text: A printed adapter that can be inserted into a drill press. The adapter can hold a 15mm PTFE rod (which does not fit into the chuck of my drill press). You can now insert the PTFE rod into the adapter and insert the adapter into the drill press using the M5 screw protruding from the bottom plate of the adapter. The rod can tightened in the adapter using the M3 screws in the bracket side flanges.

description.text:
With this costume component you will be the king/queen of the party.

Inspired by the well known squirting flower every amusing clown must wear, here you have your halloween best companion... the flower, easy and fast to print and hiding a surprise....water!!

Please have a look at the How I Designed This section to get all the details to complete your funny costume component.

Notes:

Important!

Print the part with the "face" facing the print bed. You will get the best results!

3D Printing and Post-printing

This item is easy to print. It needs no supports and the three printed parts are easy to assemble. Just the central part will need a bit of glue. You only have to make one small hole in the center of the item using a thin pin previously heated with a lighter. Pay attention to the zone where the hole must be done! It must fit the channel in the back side...

After making the hole, you must assemble the clip in the slot and make sure it keeps tightly in place.

Adding the squirting system

Well, we have the component ready but the job isn't finished yet!

We need to assemble the squirting system. For this step you need two cheap and easy to find parts:

A plastic syringe (I used a 20 ml one I had at home but bigger or smaller ones will work as well)
A piece of flexible plastic pipe. In this case we need a Ø 6 mm outer pipe as the backside conexion is designed to fit this pipe size. This is a very common item you can find in gardening stores for example.

First of all we must check the length of pipe we need in order to hide the pipe and the syringe behind our clothing. Fit the pipe in the housing the printed part has and the other end in the water-filled syringe. The pipe will go through our chest to our arm and it will finish in our hand where the syringe will do the rest...

Please note that some glue (like superglue) will be a good idea if you want to get a tight assembly and don't want to get yourself wet (see the videos to get the idea ;))

A piece of advice...

If you realize your friends are getting angry (and too wet!) it is time to stop and move to another place ;)

Notes:

This is my first print with PETG, a very nice material, but hard to find the optimum settings.
Used the heated printbed, but my extruder temp was a little too cool.
Overall it turned out okay.

Ouch...

PETG is a very nice material, it just is hard to clean up supports and little bits from the print. I discovered that the little stringers are sharp like needles... Ouch....

Printed the shell upside down, with minimal support.
The rings were printed concentric side up, with minimal support also.

Designed this in 123Design, struggling to get the shell function to operate properly for the top "shell". Getting everything to line up was also a challenge.....

The cross piece in the top shell, i used for "aligning" a PCB to vertical orientation.
I umm McGyver'd it to fit the PCB with a pair of diagonal cutters.
It is another example of "good enough is the enemy of the best" :)

Hardware used

The two parts, lower plate and top shell are held together with 3mm hardware, just be sure not over tighten things when you assemble it.

The LED RINGS are 90mm, 70mm, 50mm and can be found on Ebay.
I made a small circut that rectifies the AC from the base, Filters it with some surplus caps i had laying about, and then feeds it to a small switching regulator. I set it to about 12.5volts output.

The led rings generate a little heat, and thats the reason the top shell has some vent slots.

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/69oqwdvQFCB

This is a support ring for 70mm ostomy bag. It fits the build volume for makerbot mini. Create a belt to attach to the side loops using any 1/2" strapping and any tightening or connecting system you like. I used elastic strap, sewing, and some velcro to make it connect. I made it to fit my waist, it doesn't have much adjustment in it. You could use luggage strapping and connectors but they might add bulk, or even just loop a bathrobe belt through the handles and tie a knot in it. Thread your bag through the hole, the ring should put pressure on the front of the plastic where the flexible bag joins the snap ring, or wafer. This will allow you to put even pressure all around to help prevent surprises and add compression to the stoma site if needed. Do not use if you are experiencing herniation, as it may exacerbate the problem if you tighten it too much.
I uploaded a second one, ostomy ring fatter, which is just 5mm smaller center and 2 mm thicker so less likely to bend. I found the original one was lslipping off on one side and bending with use.
